##From siege to siege, why Italy is mired in epidemic

Italy is locked up.

Italy, already at the cusp of a new European pneumonia epidemic, is bracing itself for another unprecedented storm. On the evening of March 9 local time, Italian Prime Minister Contes announced the most "hard core" epidemic prevention measures to date: Because of the new crown epidemic, emergency control measures on the movement of people will be extended from the northern three regions to the entire Italian territory. From 10 March, cross-provincial movement of people is prohibited unless required for work or health needs. Schools across the country will remain closed until April 3, while sporting events and public events will be suspended.

As of March 9, Italy had 9,172 confirmed cases, ranking second in the world, with 463 cumulative deaths and a fatality rate of 5.04 per cent, making it one of the highest in the major affected countries.

If you turn the clock back a bit, Italy was one of the first countries to stop shipping to China in the early days of the Chinese outbreak, and was one of the first within the European Union to declare a national health emergency. In the 2019 Global Health Security Index, Italy ranked 31 / 195 in terms of its overall capacity to respond to pandemics, which is among the highest in the world, and in the "surveillance of disease" , "cross-border response" and other indicators ranked first in the world.

How can a European country with good health care, rapid response and transparent information be so affected by the epidemic? What has happened to Italy since the outbreak of community contagion in late February?

###Patient number one, long overdue

CODOGNO, with a population of just 20,000, is a small town in Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. . Patient number one here has set off a community-wide epidemic in northern Italy. Looking back, the failure to diagnose "patient number one" earlier was the first foreshadowing of the virus that would later wreak havoc across the country.

The first new coronary in Italy was a tourist couple from Wuhan who were diagnosed in Rome on January 31. A week later, another man who had just arrived in Wuhan was also diagnosed in Italy. As a result of timely detection and isolation, these three imported cases from China did not spread infection, and therefore is not considered to be epidemiological sense of "patient. ".

It was not until February 21 that the first citizen of the country to be infected with the new crown was confirmed in a hospital in the town of Cordoño. The 38-year-old man, Saint Matthias, has no clear history of exposure to China. He developed cold symptoms on Feb. 14 and was reported to his family doctor but not taken seriously. He was admitted to the emergency room on Feb. 18 with what was thought to be mild pneumonia, but he was not serious enough to be hospitalized and was sent home to rest. When he returned to the hospital on February 19, his symptoms had worsened. At the time, medical staff continued to follow the standard pneumonia procedure until an experienced anesthesiologist insisted that the hospital test him for a new coronavirus infection. On February 21, Saint Matthias tested positive.

Socially active patient number one, Saint Matthias, is believed to be a "super-spreader" , spreading the virus to at least 13 Italians before being quarantined, they included his pregnant wife, a friend who jogged with him, three guests at his friend's father's Bar, eight hospital staff and patients, and at least one elderly woman who died from her condition.

Since February 22, there has been an exponential increase in the number of confirmed cases in the northern part of the country, centered in Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. . On 23 February, the Italian government imposed a blockade on Lombardy and 11 municipalities in the Veneto region.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The flood of criticism was directed at Cordoño: It took Saint Matthias nearly a week from the onset of symptoms to remember to test the new crown; it took him at least 36 hours to get into the hospital and into quarantine, there were even visits from family and friends. After the diagnosis, there was no immediate closure of the emergency room and disinfection. The prime minister, Contes, blamed the hospital for the spread of the virus without naming it: failing to comply with the rules governing infectious diseases. Italian prosecutors are already investigating.

That may mean that the "National Health Emergency" announced by the Italian government at the end of January does not exist. According to the guidelines issued at the time, anyone with flu or pneumonia symptoms should be considered a potential new case, regardless of a clear history of exposure to China.

But in practice, the focus of Italy's early screening has almost entirely to do with China's history of exposure. The focus is on monitoring the Chinese diaspora in Italy, as well as in places like Milan, Rome and Prato, which have strong ties to China. The town of Cordoño has little contact with China, and local health care workers would have a hard time imagining the first time it would be here. This early thinking ignored the possibility that the virus had already entered the local transmission. Public experts, through more confirmed patients of the virus genetic analysis, that the virus early in "patient 1" disease weeks before the local spread.

Saint Matthias was eventually detained after his wife inadvertently revealed that he had dined with friends who were visiting China at the time. But the friend's new crown tested negative. Italy has yet to track down its "patient zero" .

###Out of step central-local relationship

Italy is divided into 20 regions, regional government in health, sports and other public utilities have an important voice, and form a complement to the central government. At present, the central government is relatively weak and the local governments are relatively strong, and the imbalance between the central and local governments has also become one of the reasons for the weakness of early epidemic prevention.

The northern regions of Lombardy and Veneto are the most economically developed in the country, contributing more than 30 percent of the country's GDP. Both districts have long been held by the far-right Coalition Party (Lega) , which launched a referendum in 2017 to seek more autonomy. During a crisis last year, Salvini, the party's leader and a well-known populist Italian politician, was kicked out of the governing coalition by his opponent, the five star movement, and so resented the new cabinet formed by the five star Alliance, which continued to be run by Contes. In the wake of the outbreak, Salvini has repeatedly said that Contes's "handling of the crisis is a disaster" and that he "should resign as soon as possible" .

When imported cases from China emerged in early February, the coalition began to take aim at the Contes administration. The four regions, chaired by the Union Party, launched a proposal to require the central government to impose a 14-day quarantine on students returning to Italy from China. At the time, the Chinese community had initiated voluntary segregation under the coordination of embassies and consulates, and the government had assessed that the measures were sufficient to prevent the imposition of segregation orders on specific ethnic groups. Contes came under fire from the coalition for his "inability to protect the Italians" .

In the wake of the outbreak, the central government and Lombardy's regional government have also disagreed over the testing criteria. The regional government believes that asymptomatic people should also be tested and that asymptomatic positive subjects should be included in the data of confirmed patients. But the central government, as if to reassure the public, says that because asymptomatic people are not the main cause of the outbreak, it is not necessary to test them, the regional government has "watered down" the data to make the outbreak look worse than it is. CONTES also engaged in a battle with Attilio Fontana, Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg.'s President, accusing each other of inaction.

The politicians'arguments faded out of the headlines after the outbreak intensified, but the disconnect between the central and local authorities and perhaps the lack of mobilisation in countries that already lacked the capacity to do so missed an early window on the epidemic. The nationwide deployment took place on March 1, when Contes signed an epidemic prevention decree dividing the country into three zones: the first 11 towns to be affected by the outbreak were "red zones" and remained closed; Three regions, including Lombardy and Veneto, as well as a province and a city, have been designated as "yellow zones" to restrict public activities; the third, where the rest are, has been regularly disinfected.

When the city closure order was extended from the "red zone" to the "yellow zone" on March 8, the contradictions between the central and local governments were pushed forward again. Veneto's president, Luca Zaia, has written to Contes, speaking out against the central government's three-colour scheme. He believes the epidemic in Veneto is getting better and should not be treated in the same way as the spread of Lombardy. He asked Contes to move Veneto out of the blockade, but Contes refused. Other local leaders accused Contes of failing to communicate effectively with them before the decision was made, and the people and regional governments were unclear about what they should do. As a result, the process of sealing off the city was very chaotic, and even citizens fled to the south.

While local opposition has not stopped Kount from sealing off the city, it will take time for the central government, which is constrained by local forces, to determine how far it can go in sealing off the city and coordinating epidemic prevention efforts.

###The structure of a highly ageing society

Early ineffectiveness sowed the seeds for an epidemic to spread, but the real killer was Italy's highly aging social structure.

Taken together, the Italian government's decision-making has been relatively swift and forceful since the outbreak began. Within two days of the detection of the infection in the community, the government quickly sealed off 11 small towns in the focus of the epidemic; when the epidemic spread further, the government decisively announced a national shutdown; and subsidized businesses affected by the epidemic. While most European countries are still concerned about the lack of testing capacity, Italy has used a new test developed at a local university to give results in four to six hours to screen potential patients for maximum benefit. The town of Vo 'Euganeo in the Veneto region has 3,041 residents, all of whom were tested and none were missed, resulting in 77 patients being screened.

But these measures did not stop death. As of March 9,463 patients had been killed by new pneumonia in Italy, just behind China; the 5.04 percent fatality rate is well above the global average of 3.4 percent. Italy has just surpassed South Korea in the number of confirmed cases, but has seven times as many deaths and 13 times as many severe cases.

Globally, older people with underlying diseases are the most likely to die, and Italy happens to be the oldest country in Europe, second only to Japan.

The Italian Ministry of Health's count of the top 105 dead showed that they were, on average, 81 years old, mostly men. Two-thirds of those who died had more than two chronic conditions, the most common being hypertension, cardiovascular disease and diabetes. The new coronavirus caused an inflammatory storm, with 42.2 per cent of the deaths occurring between the ages of 80 and 89,32.4 per cent between the ages of 70 and 79 and 8.4 per cent between 60 and 69.

Italy has the highest proportion of elderly people in Europe -- as of 2018,22.6% of the population is over 65, the highest in the European Union. Italy's median age, 45.9, is also higher than the EU's 42.8, the second highest.

Italy's elderly population of nearly 14 million is a large, high risk group. On the one hand, the government advises seniors to reduce their travel to Florida -- People over the age of 65, people with health problems, and people over the age of 75 are advised by the government to stay at home as much as possible. On the other hand, the government announced in early March that schools across the country would be suspended, one of the considerations that followed was that, although children were not susceptible to death among the newly crowned, they were likely to become a source of infection among the elderly in the family.

However, once the window for early control is missed, the overall number of infections surges and medical resources run out, the elderly are the most vulnerable groups.

Under normal circumstances, Italy has 262.5 beds per 100,000 people, which is in the middle of the EU. But by early March, with more than 1,000 new cases a day becoming the norm, medical authorities in the three hardest hit areas of the north were sounding the alarm: 95 percent of the beds in the wards were already in use, stretched to the limit. Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. has even started to transfer patients to the relatively mild Tuscan region. On March 8th the Prime Minister had to sign a decree calling for 200,000 medical workers to be sent to the worst hit areas.

Medical institutions also have to make tough ethical choices. On 7 March, the Italian Intensive Care Association Siaarti issued its "15 ethical recommendations" on the treatment of new crowns, stating that in order to maximize the benefit of the majority, it is necessary to set an age limit for admission to the ICU, reserve resources for "those most likely to survive" and "those with more years to live" . In other words, when medical resources are in short supply, doctors are likely to give priority to the young, while the old are likely to lose their lives.

###Europe's divided allies

The lack of timely and effective assistance from outside, particularly from European allies, is the external cause of Italy's continued predicament.

With the first confirmed case of a new coronary disease in Cyprus on March 9,27 EU countries are finally "immune" . With the exception of the worst affected Italy, Germany, France and Spain have all had more than, confirmed cases. Many observers say the new crown epidemic is the biggest challenge facing European countries in the wake of the 2015 refugee crisis.

When Italy first decided to ground its flights to China in late January, it hoped to persuade other EU countries to follow suit. Under Schengen Convention, if only one EU country restricts flights, the effect will be limited. But most EU countries turned down the request, with only the Czech Republic deciding to restrict flights.

Last week, Italy tried to ask the EU through its civil protection mechanism for protection supplies, but member states refused. Italy had hoped that the European Union would co-ordinate purchases and distribute them according to the severity of the outbreak. However, in the case of the epidemic, most member countries have their hands full and want to keep masks and other protective materials in their countries. Both Germany and France have now banned the export of face masks. Last weekend, Germany also intercepted a mask van bound for Switzerland.

As a supranational organization, the EU has very limited ability to bind its member states and plays a coordinating role. One EU diplomat told Politico that health policy was "a national function, not an EU function" and that the EU could not interfere with whether member states grounded flights, sealed off cities or deployed epidemic supplies. The EU's function is simply to nudge member states towards co-ordination.

The European Center for Disease Control (ECDC) is the European Union's Coordinating Organization for the Prevention and Control of Infectious Diseases, established in 2003 after the outbreak of SARS. On February 24th the ECDC joined World Health Organization in sending a team of experts to Italy. But critics say the European Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (ECDC) is not playing its part in the new outbreak.

An editorial in the Financial Times said the EU should ease fiscal discipline to help Italy deal with the outbreak. The EU requires member states to have deficit ratios of no more than 3 per cent. The northern regions most affected by the epidemic are the economic engine of Italy. The EU has yet to respond to the idea that a proper loosening of restrictions and a bit more room for government budget increases would help prevent the outbreak.
